Three coupled changes in `apps/desktop/src/components/dependencies/`:

**1. `useDependencyGraph.ts` — fetch plans in parallel with issues**

At the top of the file, add a height helper:
```ts
function computeNodeHeight(phaseCount: number | undefined): number {
  if (phaseCount === undefined || phaseCount <= 1) return phaseCount === 1 ? 50 : 60;
  if (phaseCount <= 3) return 60;
  if (phaseCount <= 6) return 75;
  return 90;
}
```
Note the asymmetric handling: `undefined` (no plan yet) returns 60 (default), but `1` explicitly returns 50 (smaller).

Extend `FetchedIssue` with `phaseCount?: number`.

In the fetch useEffect, parallel-invoke `get_plan` alongside `fetch_github_issue_by_number`:
```ts
Promise.all(
  release.issues.map(async (issue) => {
    const [details, plan] = await Promise.all([
      invoke<FetchedIssue>('fetch_github_issue_by_number', {
        number: issue.number,
        projectPath: activeProject?.path ?? null,
      }).catch(() => ({ number: issue.number, title: issue.title, body: undefined, state: 'open' })),
      invoke<{ phases?: unknown[] } | null>('get_plan', {
        issueNumber: issue.number,
        tikiPath: null,  // resolves to cwd/.tiki — matches existing get_state pattern
      }).catch(() => null),
    ]);
    return {
      ...details,
      phaseCount: Array.isArray(plan?.phases) ? plan.phases.length : undefined,
    };
  })
)
```
Note `tikiPath: null` — `get_plan` resolves to `cwd/.tiki` when omitted (commands.rs:141-144). This matches how `get_state` is invoked elsewhere.

**2. `useDependencyGraph.ts` — pass per-node height to dagre + thread phaseCount to node data**

Modify `layoutGraph` to accept node heights:
```ts
function layoutGraph(nodes: IssueNodeType[], edges: Edge[], heights: Map<string, number>) {
  // ...
  nodes.forEach((node) => {
    const h = heights.get(node.id) ?? 60;
    g.setNode(node.id, { width: 200, height: h });
  });
  // ...
  const layoutedNodes = nodes.map((node) => {
    const pos = g.node(node.id);
    const h = heights.get(node.id) ?? 60;
    return { ...node, position: { x: pos.x - 100, y: pos.y - h / 2 } };
  });
}
```
Note: `pos.y - h/2` replaces the hardcoded `pos.y - 30` so variable heights still center on dagre's computed y. This is what keeps swimlane rank grouping intact (rank y-centers stay consistent; only the box around them grows/shrinks).

Build the heights map and pass `phaseCount` into `IssueNodeData`:
```ts
const heights = new Map<string, number>();
const nodes: IssueNodeType[] = fetchedIssues.map((issue) => {
  const h = computeNodeHeight(issue.phaseCount);
  heights.set(String(issue.number), h);
  return {
    id: String(issue.number),
    type: 'issue' as const,
    position: { x: 0, y: 0 },
    data: {
      issueNumber: issue.number,
      title: issue.title,
      status: resolveStatus(issue),
      phaseProgress: resolvePhaseProgress(issue),
      phaseCount: issue.phaseCount,
    },
  };
});
// ...
const layouted = layoutGraph(nodes, edges, heights);
```

**3. `IssueNode.tsx` — render the height**

Extend `IssueNodeData`:
```ts
export type IssueNodeData = {
  issueNumber: number;
  title: string;
  status: 'pending' | 'executing' | 'completed' | 'failed' | 'open' | 'closed';
  phaseProgress?: { current: number; total: number };
  phaseCount?: number;
};
```

In the component, compute the height locally so the rendered box matches dagre's allocation. Use the same helper-equivalent inline (or duplicate the function — both modules want it):
```tsx
const nodeHeight = data.phaseCount === undefined ? 60 : data.phaseCount <= 1 ? 50 : data.phaseCount <= 3 ? 60 : data.phaseCount <= 6 ? 75 : 90;
```

Apply via inline style on the root div:
```tsx
<div className={`issue-node issue-node-${data.status}`} style={{ minHeight: nodeHeight }}>
```

Using `minHeight` (not `height`) — content can still push the box taller if needed (e.g., a long title that wraps), but the floor matches dagre's allocation. Progress bar already `position: absolute; bottom: 0` so it sticks to whatever the box ends up being (preserves #149 Phase 2).

No CSS changes needed — `.issue-node` is already `position: relative` (IssueNode.css:127). The progress bar's absolute positioning naturally re-anchors to the new bottom edge.

**Why not adjust width too:** the issue explicitly forbids it. Variable widths would break swimlane band rank-grouping from #149 Phase 1, which rounds y-positions. Heights vary; x stays aligned per rank.
